cent appearance of a new UAR military mission in Saudi Arabia reflects the gradual improvement in Saudi-UAR relations which has accelerated since the development of the Communist threat in Iraq. Egyptian military personnel have been observed during July at the Saudi army training center at Taif and also at the al-Kharj military post; in late May a military mission was expected to arrive in mid-June to train tribal irregulars, the so-called \"white army.\"\n\nThe American Embassy in Saudi Arabia reports that the chief of the United States military advisory group there is concerned that the UAR mission may attempt to discredit American advisory assistance. The possibility that the Saudis may be considering curtailment of at least some of the American group's activities is suggested from the Saudi Army's director of maintenance and transport, requesting the maintenance branches of the Taif and al-Kharj military posts to report the number of American advisers, how much they were needed, and the possibility of getting along without them. UAR inspiration of this Saudi request, however, is not certain.\n\nA large UAR military mission was withdrawn from Saudi Arabia in March 1958 as a consequence of the diplomatic crisis caused by King Saud's efforts to incite an anti-Nasir conspiracy in Syria. Return of a UAR mission to Saudi Arabia, as part of an outward normalization of relations between the two countries, is reported to have been under consideration by Crown Prince Faysal for nearly a year.\n\nNasir has shown readiness to cooperate with Crown Prince Faysal, but he spurned a recent attempt by Saud to capitalize on the improved atmosphere. Despite the UAR ambassador's belief that Saud, in traveling to Europe via the Suez Canal, was eager to create an opportunity to meet Nasir, the latter sent Vice President Marshal Amir to greet the chief of state", "token_count": 312, "token_end_0based": 311, "token_start_0based": 0, "token_text": "ii asia-africa uar military mission reappears in saudi arabia the recent appearance of a new uar military mission in saudi arabia reflects the gradual improvement in saudi-uar relations which has accelerated since the development of the communist threat in iraq egyptian military personnel have been observed during july at the saudi army training center at taif and also at the al-kharj military post in late may a military mission was expected to arrive in mid-june to train tribal irregulars the so-called white army the american embassy in saudi arabia reports that the chief of the united states military advisory group there is concerned that the uar mission may attempt to discredit american advisory assistance the possibility that the saudis may be considering curtailment of at least some of the american group's activities is suggested from the saudi army's director of maintenance and transport requesting the maintenance branches of the taif and al-kharj military posts to report the number of american advisers how much they were needed and the possibility of getting along without them uar inspiration of this saudi request however is not certain a large uar military mission was withdrawn from saudi arabia in march 1958 as a consequence of the diplomatic crisis caused by king saud's efforts to incite an anti-nasir conspiracy in syria return of a uar mission to saudi arabia as part of an outward normalization of relations between the two countries is reported to have been under consideration by crown prince faysal for nearly a year nasir has shown readiness to cooperate with crown prince faysal but he spurned a recent attempt by saud to capitalize on the improved atmosphere despite the uar ambassador's belief that saud in traveling to europe via the suez canal was eager to create an opportunity to meet nasir the latter sent vice president marshal amir to greet the chief of state", "unred_source_page": 8}
